dismissalText.commentary: Rikki Clarke b Shoaib Akhtar 39 (47b 3x4 0x6 54m) SR: 82.97

dismissalComment.html: cleaned up by Shoaib, lethal! Full and fast, Clarke goes for a nothing swish with zero footwork and the ball comes in from offstump and rearranges the furniture to send him back into the hut, but it was a key innings of 39, did England much good you would have to say given the situation

dismissalText.commentary: Younis Khan c Pietersen b Clarke 55 (89b 9x4 0x6 108m) SR: 61.79

dismissalComment.html: Clarke strikes! That was a half volley on middle and leg, Younis hits it with the breeze, picks it off the legs and the bail sails high and fast down towards deep midwicket, looks destined for six but Pietersen in the deep takes a good catch right on the ropes! That was agonizingly close to the ropes but KP held his nerve to hold the catch, Younis departs for a fine innings, is this a breakthrough England can build on?

commentTextItems.html: thats it, all over, in the slot outside off and its lazily driven through the covers for four to seal the deal! Its been an overcast, gloomy day but Pakistan have outclassed England with bat and ball. Chasing 167 to win, they reached home with seven wickets to spare, key knock from Younis, Yousuf and Inzamam worth their weight in gold, and Pakistan take a 1-0 series lead

commentPostTextItems.html: In the dark, to get 42 from 26 balls was a supreme effort from Inzamam, but the steady hands of Younis and Yousuf steadied the ship after the loss of the openers. For England, Lewis bowled an exceptional spell, much like Mohammad Asif did for Pakistan earlier in the day, but that was about it. With the D/L method coming in to play during the rain-reduced England innings and the miserably overcast Pakistan chase, it was not an entire day's cricket but we atleast have a result to kick the series alive.

England have some issues to sort out - batting, bowling - and they will desperately need to improve their ODI game with some key fixtures lined up in the coming season. Pakistan will have taken some solid confidence from this win after losing the Test series. Overall, a lack of confidence on England's part was their outdoing and Pakistan's fiery pace attack came together early and their depth in batting stepped it up in testing conditions.
Today's Man of the Match is Shoaib Akhtar for his awesome spell of 4 for 28 that helped dismantle England earlier in the day.

Three games to go in this NatWest Series, do join us for Cricinfo's continued coverage of the contest when the third match begins at Southampton on Tuesday. Until then, this is Jamie Alter signing off with a hearty cheers and good night!

slow yorker on off is punched to point
slower ball on middle and off is worked through midwicket
full on off, played to mid-off

commentPreTextItems.html: Yousuf was short of the crease on that last run, so they only got one, the double was scrapped

commentTextItems.html: full outside off, moves forward and is rapped on the pads, loud appeal is rightly turned down
middle and leg and its whipped through square and they can get a run easily in this gloom, well run
four more to Inzamam, in lucky style! Flashes hard at one on off, leading edge flies to Gough at third man who cant see a thing in the gloom and drops the catch, and gives away four runs

dismissalComment.html: Clarke strikes! That was a half volley on middle and leg, Younis hits it with the breeze, picks it off the legs and the bail sails high and fast down towards deep midwicket, looks destined for six but Pietersen in the deep takes a good catch right on the ropes! That was agonizingly close to the ropes but KP held his nerve to hold the catch, Younis departs for a fine innings, is this a breakthrough England can build on?

stories.title: 'We have a decent chance of bouncing back' - Strauss
stories.subTitle: England v Pakistan, 2nd ODI, Lord's
stories.summary: Andrew Strauss insisted England would be a "lot better" by the time of next year's World Cup after they slumped to the eighth limited-overs defeat of his captaincy

stories.title: Still more to come from Shoaib
stories.subTitle: England v Pakistan, 2nd ODI, Lord's
stories.summary: Shoaib Akhtar is just three matches into his comeback but already he's gone past the 90mph mark with regularity against England

stories.title: Shoaib and Asif light up a gloomy Lord's
stories.subTitle: England v Pakistan, 2nd ODI, Lord's
stories.summary:
Shoaib Akhtar and Mohammad Asif lit up a gloomy day at Lord's with two
outstanding spells of pace bowling to set up Pakistan for an seven-wicket
win
stories.byline: The Bulletin by Andrew McGlashan at Lord's

stories.title: Rain set to come into play again
stories.subTitle: England v Pakistan, 2nd ODI, Lord's
stories.summary: The weather again looks set to play a big part in the second ODI at Lord's on Saturday. Rain washed out the first match at Cardiff on Wednesday with Pakistan set for victory, and the forecast for London tomorrow is poor.
